# klaviyo-event-pipeline-demo — Cursor context

## What this project is
A Python event pipeline simulator demonstrating real-time event
ingestion, fan-out routing, backpressure, and dead-letter queue
patterns — analogous to Klaviyo's events platform architecture.

This is an interview portfolio project. Code quality and clarity
matter more than performance optimization.

## Stack + conventions
- Python 3.12, Pydantic v2, asyncio, pytest
- uv for dependency management (not pip)
- Type hints on ALL functions — no untyped code
- Docstrings on ALL classes and public methods
- snake_case for variables/functions, PascalCase for classes
- No external dependencies beyond pydantic and pytest
- No real Kafka, Redis, or database — in-memory only

## Module responsibilities (do not mix concerns)
- models.py     → Pydantic schemas ONLY. No business logic.
- producer.py   → EventProducer class. Emit, validate, throttle.
- router.py     → EventRouter class. Receive from queue, dispatch.
- handlers.py   → Handler classes. Each handles its event types.
- metrics.py    → MetricsCollector class. Track throughput/latency.
- main.py       → Demo runner. Glues everything together.
- test_pipeline.py → pytest tests. One test file for the whole project.

## Event types (use these names exactly)
- placed_order
- viewed_product
- abandoned_cart
- clicked_email

## Key design decisions already made
1. EventProducer uses asyncio.Queue for the main event queue
2. EventRouter runs in an async loop, consuming from the queue
3. Fan-out: router dispatches to ALL registered handlers per event
4. Backpressure: if queue.qsize() > BACKPRESSURE_THRESHOLD (default 100),
   producer sleeps for THROTTLE_DELAY_MS before next emit
5. DLQ: a separate asyncio.Queue; handlers push failed events there
6. Metrics: dict-based, updated in-place, no external metrics lib

## What NOT to do
- Do not add external dependencies (no kafka-python, redis, etc.)
- Do not use print() for logging — use Python logging module
- Do not use threading — asyncio only
- Do not add HTTP endpoints or API layers
- Do not use global state outside MetricsCollector
- Do not write synchronous handlers — all handlers are async

## Testing conventions
- Each test function tests ONE behavior
- Use pytest-asyncio for async tests (add to uv deps if needed)
- Test names: test__ e.g. test_producer_backpressure
- Always test the DLQ: invalid events MUST land in DLQ, not be silently dropped
- Test metrics: throughput and error rate must update after events are processed
